00:46.115 --> 00:57.949
What would you think would be some of the 
outstanding developments in your area of

00:46.115 --> 00:57.949
petroleum engineering, say, since 1938, that 
you've come to Shamrock? Well, of course, my

00:58.975 --> 01:05.442
experience in petroleum engineering was largely 
while I was with the Lone Star Gas Company. When I

01:06.323 --> 01:11.869
came with Diamond Shamrock, my experience was 
administrative management. But I imagine you

01:12.370 --> 01:17.135
kept up with the developments in the field to a 
certain extent anyway. Well, to tell you the

01:18.797 --> 01:26.586
truth, there's been so much progress made in that 
field that I hardly speak the language anymore.

01:30.329 --> 01:42.862
The science and engineering in the oil industry 
has advanced beyond belief over this period of

01:30.329 --> 01:42.862
time. You see, in my early experience in the oil 
business, waste was the rule rather than the

01:44.183 --> 01:55.915
exception. And there was an oversupply of both oil 
and gas. And when I came up to Amarillo to work for

02:03.261 --> 02:20.706
the Shamrock, oil was selling for 50 cents a barrel 
and gas at a penny a thousand cubic feet. And nobody

02:23.232 --> 02:30.020
gave much importance on reserves. For 
perspective, what's it selling for today? Well,

02:33.383 --> 02:45.937
the oil is selling for about $10 a barrel, and gas, 
intrastate gas, is selling for $1,000 and more.

02:47.018 --> 02:52.885
The interstate gas, the price is regulated by the 
Federal Power Commission has been adjusted

02:54.232 --> 03:02.623
upwards to 45,000 cents per thousand cubic feet. 
And there's not much gas available

03:03.824 --> 03:10.073
at that price. So it's an entirely new ballgame. 
And in my early experience in the... oil and gas

03:22.210 --> 03:28.796
business, mostly gas, while I was with the Lone 
Star Gas Company.

03:29.077 --> 03:49.416
I ran experiments and did a lot of development work 
in the field toward conservation of gas, to cut out

03:29.077 --> 03:49.416
the waste of gas, and wrote a number of papers on 
that subject

03:50.662 --> 03:56.210
during a time when no one seemed to be much 
interested in conserving gas. But those

03:57.372 --> 04:03.120
practices have developed to where now there's 
very little waste. I served as chairman of the

04:05.003 --> 04:18.863
engineering committee to study the panhandle 
waste during the period of time when it was legal to

04:05.003 --> 04:18.863
blow gas into the air to get the liquids out. 
There's some four billion cubic feet of gas wasted

04:19.754 --> 04:28.042
before they were able to get the laws passed to stop 
the waste. I testified in the Senate

04:28.062 --> 04:37.451
Investigating Committee and the coal committee 
from Congress investigating that waste. And

04:37.691 --> 04:48.782
finally, in 1935, they repealed the stripping law 
and cut out this large waste of gas. but the

04:49.606 --> 05:08.866
Railroad Commission had many, many lawsuits from 
people resisting the law and challenging the law

04:49.606 --> 05:08.866
before they ever were able to establish their 
conservation rules and regulations. In a way, I

05:08.886 --> 05:18.195
guess you could say that between, say, 1938 and 
now, the biggest change has been, outside of the

05:08.886 --> 05:18.195
increased technology, would be that earlier it 
was a product looking for a market, and today it's a

05:18.479 --> 05:23.286
market looking for a product. Well, that's true. 
That substantially tells the whole story. And

05:30.076 --> 05:41.592
when a commodity becomes valuable, then the 
industry itself will eliminate the waste because

05:30.076 --> 05:41.592
it pays them to do so.

